    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The light reactions are like a high-speed assembly line where sunlight is the raw material that gets converted into usable energy currency. First, photons hit the chlorophyll in the thylakoid membranes, exciting electrons to a higher energy state. These high-energy electrons are passed down an electron transport chain, which pumps protons into the thylakoid space to create a gradient. This gradient drives ATP synthase to make ATP, while the electrons eventually reduce NADP+ to form NADPH. It's essentially a solar-powered battery charger that uses light to charge the cell's energy banks.",
